{"id":"katahdin-woods-and-waters-scenic-byway","generatedAt":"2026-07-12T01:11:51.097Z","designation":"National Scenic Byway","parkCode":null,"source":{"roadArticle":"Maine State Route 11","revisionId":1350635020,"url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maine_State_Route_11"},"attribution":{"license":"CC BY-SA 4.0","licenseUrl":"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/","articleUrl":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maine_State_Route_11","text":"Route, junction, and history details adapted from the Wikipedia article \"Maine State Route 11\", by Wikipedia contributors, licensed under CC BY-SA 4.0."},"sources":[{"name":"Wikipedia","src":"wikipedia","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maine_State_Route_11","revisionId":1350635020,"retrievedAt":"2026-07-12T01:11:51.097Z"},{"name":"Federal Highway Administration — National Scenic Byways","src":"fhwa","url":"https://www.fhwa.dot.gov/byways","retrievedAt":"2026-07-12T01:11:51.097Z"},{"name":"OpenStreetMap contributors (ODbL)","src":"osm","url":"https://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright","retrievedAt":"2026-07-12T01:11:51.097Z"}],"endpoints":{"from":"Lebanon, ME","to":"Fort Kent, ME","via":["Minot, ME","Benton, ME","Patten, ME"]},"itinerary":[],"history":{"paragraphs":["The number 11 dates back to 1922 when the New England road marking system was adopted, although Maine did not take part until 1925. New England Route 11 was known as the Manchester-Biddeford Route, as it began in Manchester, Vermont and ended in Biddeford, Maine. The Maine section of Route 11 ran for 29 miles (47 km). It followed the current routing of US 202/SR 11 between Lebanon and downtown Sanford, continued northeast into Alfred along modern US 202, then through Lyman and Arundel along modern SR 111 to terminate at Route 1 (the modern intersection of US 1 and SR 111) in Biddeford.","In 1926, the U.S. Numbered Highway System was established and superseded the New England Interstate system. Some of the New England Interstate routes were integrated into the new system (such as Route 1, which became part of US 1). Route 11 did not become a U.S. Highway but was one of several that were redesignated as state highways and kept their existing numbers. State Route 11 was officially designated in 1926 and kept its existing routing until 1933.","In 1931, the Maine State Highway Commission conducted an experiment in which it designated a new low-numbered state highway (SR 4) which ran mostly on existing alignments of the original 1925 intrastate routes (which were all numbered 100 and higher to avoid conflicts with the New England Interstate routes) and replaced several of the original numbers along those alignments. This effectively created a long interregional route that covered an important travel corridor between the New Hampshire and Canadian borders, all with a single route number.","This experiment proved to be a success, and the SHC decided to expand the interregional route system across the entire state highway system using low route numbers, including those from the original New England routes. Three-digit route numbers (and larger two-digit numbers) would be used to fill in shorter alignments to complement the interregional routes. This process began in 1933 and was finished in 1934. Many of the existing 1925 routes were truncated, overlapped with the new routes, or eliminated altogether. Routes which were completely eliminated generally had their numbers reassigned somewhere else in the system. By the time the renumbering project was finished, SR 11 was extended to 400 miles (640 km)."],"sourceSection":"History","src":"wikipedia"},"highlights":[{"n":"Lebanon","d":"The drive begins here","q":"Lebanon","lat":43.39444444,"lng":-70.85083333,"src":"wikipedia"},{"n":"Fort Kent","d":"The drive ends here","q":"Fort Kent","lat":47.24194444,"lng":-68.57222222,"src":"wikipedia"}],"references":[{"n":1,"text":"MaineDOT Public Map Viewer","url":"https://www.maine.gov/mdot/mapviewer/?show=Conserved%20Lands%2CContours%2CInterstate%20Interchanges%2CRail%20Bridges%2CRoads%20General%2CState%20Urban%2CTown%20and%20County%20Boundaries%2CWater%20Bodies%2CWetlands&hide=Contours%20-%202%20foot%2CFederal%20Urban%2CMEDOT%20Regions%2CMetropolitan%20Planning%20Areas%202015&added=Bridges%20-%20All%2CCulverts%20-%20Large%2CMajor%20Signs%2CNodes%2CTraffic%20Signals%2CAirports%2CFerry%20Routes%2CRailroads%2CBuildings%2CLots%2CMost%20Recent%20Highway%20Treatment%2CFederal%20Functional%20Class%2CHighway%20Corridor%20Priority%2CJurisdiction%2CNational%20Highway%20System%2CNAIP%202015&transparency=100&center=47.251014%2C-68.594277&z=213"},{"n":2,"text":"Floodgap Roadgap's RoadsAroundME: Maine State Route 11A Deprecated link archived 2012-03-12 at archive.today[self-published source]","url":"http://www.floodgap.com/roadgap/me/r?11a"},{"n":3,"text":"\"Floodgap Roadgap's RoadsAroundME: Maine State Route 11A\". www.floodgap.com. Retrieved January 25, 2022.","url":"https://www.floodgap.com/roadgap/me/r?11a"},{"n":4,"text":"\"Floodgap Roadgap's RoadsAroundME: Maine State Route 11\". www.floodgap.com. Retrieved January 29, 2022.","url":"https://www.floodgap.com/roadgap/me/r?11"},{"n":5,"text":"\"Floodgap Roadgap's RoadsAroundME: Maine State Route 15\". www.floodgap.com. Retrieved January 29, 2022.","url":"https://www.floodgap.com/roadgap/me/r?15"},{"n":6,"text":"\"Google Maps\". Google Maps. Retrieved January 29, 2022.","url":"https://www.google.com/maps/@45.0669224,-68.9365259,3a,37.5y,16.83h,83.95t/data=!3m6!1e1!3m4!1s07ou3fmZ2_h6xs567sZNKQ!2e0!7i13312!8i6656"},{"n":7,"text":"\"SR 11B\" (Map). Google Maps. Retrieved May 7, 2017.","url":"https://www.google.com/maps/dir/45.6573674,-68.709239/45.6538826,-68.7102342/@45.6560925,-68.7130632,17z/data=!3m1!4b1!4m2!4m1!3e0"},{"n":8,"text":"\"Google Maps\". Google Maps. Retrieved January 30, 2022.","url":"https://www.google.com/maps/@45.6573917,-68.7089217,3a,37.5y,289.98h,91.42t/data=!3m6!1e1!3m4!1sA3H0uA520nHvk_SCXBQkPg!2e0!7i13312!8i6656"}],"routeLine":[[44.31487,-69.8107